You could use neutrino or gravity-wave astronomy, but maybe that counts as
peeking out of the box. The only other way is to measure the tidal force.
For example, suspend a sphere of dust (noninteracting particles at rest) in
the middle of the box. In outer space it will remain spherical, but in orbit
it will gradually deform into an ellipsoid. Or float a bunch of bathroom
scales aligned in different planes; if you're in orbit there will be a
slight dependence of the zero point on the alignment.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Did Gravity Probe B give an example of such a measurement?
">

I think it was something like that.

