[I assume that the orbit is sufficiently far from M that a
human astronaut could survive in the orbiting boxcar. For
earth and sun this is valid for any possible orbit, but
not necessarily so near a truly enormous mass.]

Take 7 small test masses and release one at the center-of-mass of boxcar
plus contents; release the other six &quot;above&quot;, &quot;below&quot;, &quot;in front&quot;, &quot;in
back&quot;, &quot;to the left&quot; and &quot;to the right&quot; of the first (selecting the
terms in quotes arbitrarily but consistently). Be sure to release them
carefully so the releasing does not impart any spin or velocity to them
(relative to the box), and also be sure that the boxcar is filled with
vacuum (or put them inside a vacuum chamber within it), as air currents
would otherwise completely dominate any gravitational effects. Now watch
them carefully and accurately: in deep space they will not move relative
to each other or to the boxcar, but in orbit they will. Moreover, how
they move will tell you which way is down, and in which direction the
boxcar's orbit is traveling; very accurate measurements can even tell
you the radius of the orbit and the value of M. Remarkably, you can (in
principle at least) determine the value of M without knowing the masses
of your test objects or boxcar.

Exercise for the reader: explain how one interprets the
motions of the test masses in terms of the boxcar's orbit:
how does one determine down? forward? radius? M?
Hint: you will need exquisite measurement accuracy for
their positions, and good timing accuracy for r and M.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Did Gravity Probe B give an example of such a measurement?
">

I believe their initial &quot;geodetic&quot; results are related, but the actual
experiment is to measure the precession of gyroscopes, not the motion of
freefalling test masses. Note their telescope monitoring the guide star
was used as the necessary orientation required to accurately establish a
locally inertial frame, relative to which they can measure the
precession. The above gedanken requires much better position accuracy
than is really feasible; GPB required vastly better orientation accuracy
than is feasible using local measurements, so they used a distant star.

Tom Roberts
