Others have said how, in principle, you could tell which box
you were in.  However, the title of your post refers to the
equivalence principle which states that it is not possible to
distinguish between two inertial frames in this way and I
wonder if this was the point of your post.

In order to reconcile these two positions you must remember
that the equivalence principle applies to an arbitrarily small
volume of space.  In other words, if it is possible to tell
which box you are in then the box is too big.

Ultimately, with a small enough box, it is not possible to tell
which one you are in.

Martin Hogbin
